{
  "answer": "**The work is *Slokāntara* (unknown author), Chapter 1.**[^1]\n\nThis argument appears in verse 47 (Slo_47), which lists the requested flaws in nature, the moon, the ocean, and the gods Viṣṇu, Indra, and Śaṅkara (Śiva), before concluding that humans are even more flawed:\n\n> *The lotus is full of thorns; the snowy mountain has its cold; the sandalwood tree is inhabited by serpents;*  \n> *The sun is fierce; the moon has a body stained by a hare; the ocean has salty water;*  \n> *Viṣṇu was a cowherd; Indra is exceedingly fickle; Śaṅkara has a blue throat;*  \n> *All these have flaws; how much more so will people on earth have flaws?* || 47 ||[^2]\n\nThe commentary on this verse elaborates that these are indeed flaws (*doṣa*), including Śaṅkara's blue throat from the *kālakūṭa* poison, and stresses that nothing—even the gods—is flawless.[^3]\n\n[^1]: *Slokāntara*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Slokāntara*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-9647e1).\n\n[^3]: *Slokāntara*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-c5d550).",
